04750nam a22006615i 9789400604377DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20222022ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97894006043777 a10.1515/97894006043772doi  a(DE-B1597)649957  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 4aG155.A65 7aHIS0260002bisacsh04a338.479109174927223/eng/202304131 aDaam, Jasmin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTourism and the Emergence of Nation-States in the Arab Eastern Mediterranean, 1920s-1930s /cJasmin Daam. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2022] 4cÂ©2022  a1 online resource (352 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCritical, Connected Histories ;v500tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tList of illustrations -- tAcknowledgements -- tNote on Transliteration -- tAbbreviations -- tChapter 1. Introduction -- tChapter 2. Space of sovereignty: Abolishing the colonial order of tourism in Egypt? -- tChapter 3. New tourists, new attractions, 'New Palestine': Implementing a new tourist space in Mandate Palestine -- tChapter 4. Contested rule and fragmented space in French Mandate Syria -- tChapter 5. Lebanon: The tourist nation-state -- tConclusion: Tourist transformations -- tNotes on persons, associations and enterprises -- tIndex of persons, associations and enterprises -- tIndex of places0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  a"In the aftermath of World War I, the beaten paths of tourism guided an increasing number of international tourists to the hinterlands of the Arab Eastern Mediterranean, where they would admire pyramids and Roman ruins. Yet they were not the only visitors: Arab nationalists gathered in summer resorts, and Yishuvi skiing clubs practised on Lebanese mountain slopes. By catering to these travellers, local tour guides and advocates of tourism development pursued their agendas. The book unearths unexpected connections between tourism and the emergence of nation-states in Egypt, Palestine, Syria and Lebanon. Arab middle-class actors striving for independence, Zionist settlers and mandate officials presented their visions of the post-Ottoman spatial order to an international audience of tourists. At the same time, mobilities and infrastructures of tourism shaped the material conditions of this order. Tourism thus helps us to understand the transformations of Arab societies in their global context, and its history is a colourful story of the emergence of the modern Middle East. "  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0https://www.aup.nl/en/publish/open-access  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aNation-state. 0aTourismzArab countriesxHistoryy20th century. 4aColonial Studies. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aMiddle East. 4aPolitics and Government. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / General.2bisacsh  aTourism, Middle East, nation-building, imperialism, spatial order.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Classical Studies 2022 Englishz978311099291508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Classical Studies 2022z9783110992878oZDB-23-DGD40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789400604377zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789400604377zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789400604377/original  a978-3-11-099291-5 EBOOK PACKAGE Classical Studies 2022 Englishb2022  a978-3-11-099389-9 EBOOK PACKAGE 